Come morning, he wakes and helps the sun into his chariot and so wears out the ever-rolling years until his death.
Apart from ceremony, this poor creature who spends his days in toil and his nights in sleep is better off than the king.
The peasant enjoys his country’s peace without ever worrying his dull head about the vigil the king must keep to maintain that peace.
